        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇧🇩 Bangladesh reintroduces 'except Israel' inscription on passports</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">On Sunday, Bangladesh's interim government restored the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-04-2025-valid-for-all-countries-except-israel-note" target="_blank">"valid for all countries except Israel" note</a> on its passports, banning citizens from traveling to Israel. It overturns a 2021 decision by the previous government, which had removed the clause to meet international passport standards. Israeli passport holders are not allowed into Bangladesh, as the country doesn't recognize Israel. The ban also extends to the two million ethnic Palestinians with Israeli citizenship.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The reinstatement coincides with <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-04-2025-br2-9-widespread-public-anger" target="_blank">widespread public anger</a> over Israel's military actions in Gaza. 100,000 estimated people attended pro-Palestine rallies in Bangladesh’s capital, Dhaka, last weekend. The protestors waved Palestinian flags and chanted the usual slogans. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
