          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What was Operation Cyclone?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/reagan-afghan-mujahideen-white-house-meeting.png" alt="President Reagan met with Afghan mujahideen in the White House to discuss the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>President Reagan met with Afghan mujahideen in the White House to discuss the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan. Credits: Michael Evans</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Operation Cyclone was the code name for the CIA program to arm and fund the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-04-2025-f1-10-afghan-mujahideen" target="_blank">Afghan mujahideen</a> in Afghanistan from 1979 to 1992. It was started as a way to halt the military intervention by the USSR in support of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The operation started under Jimmy Carter and was massively expanded by Ronald Reagan. The program became one of the most protracted and expensive CIA operations, eventually costing over $3B. Funds were routed through Pakistan’s intelligence agency, the ISI, which disproportionately supported Islamist factions favored by Pakistani dictator General Zia-ul-Haq. These groups, often the most extreme, gained the lion’s share of resources, arms, and recruits.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The operation was successful in getting the Soviets to withdraw from Afghanistan in 1989, but it wasn't without dire consequences. After the war, many fighters, including Osama bin Laden, later became involved in global jihadist movements, this time armed with battlefield experience. Some of them might have joined these extremist movements as a means of welfare, as they weren’t taken care of after the war.  
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Critics and some historians believe that Operation Cyclone was <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-04-2025-f1-11-a-stepping-stone" target="_blank">a stepping stone</a> for the rise of al-Qaeda and the Taliban. It built an ecosystem of radicalized, well-equipped fighters with no postwar reintegration plan. What started as a Cold War strategy morphed into one of the most consequential blowbacks in modern geopolitical history, one that would come back to haunt the US on September 11, 2001.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
